bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Vice President for Development and University Relations of The George Washington University reports to the President. The name changed to Vice President for Development and Alumni Affairs in 1992 and again to Vice President for Advancement in 2002. Under the Vice President are the Associate Vice President for Advancement, Central University, the Associate Vice President for School Programs, and Associate Vice President for the Medical Center. These offices raise money for University operations and oversee fund raising campaigns and endowments to the University.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include pamphlets, biographical sketches, correspondence, news releases, memorandums, photographs, videotape, and publications. They range in date from 1820 to 2003, and were transferred to the University Archives by the Vice President for Development and University Relations. Note: Not all series are processed. Ask staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into eight series: Departmental files; Alumni achievement awards; Honorary alumni; Photographs; Long range planing workbooks; Campus renderings; "GW giving"; and Fundraising and development.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series is a collection of photographs that range in date from 1895 to 1983. They include individuals, the 1967 commencement, the 1959 Glee Club, buildings, and more. Some of the individuals include Adelaide Hasse, Ainsworth Spofford, and Patricia Roberts Harris. Some of the buildings include the Law Center, Gelman Library, Thurston Hall, 2000 Pennsylvania Avenue, Academic Center Construction, and Funger Hall.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series is a two copies of a long range planing workbook for The George Washington University that was copyrighted in 1970. It includes factors influencing design, physical considerations, large area relationships, program, planning proposals, and implementation.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series is a collection of renderings of campus buildings and scenes. They range in date from 1972 to 1985. The renderings include the Cloyd Heck Marvin Center, Dorothy Betts Marvin Theater, School of Medicine and Health Sciences, University Yard, Jacob Burns Law Library and Stockton Hall, University Yard, National Law Center, Alumni House, Academic Cluster [Center], Woodhull House, Eye Street Mall, Charles E. Smith Center for Physical Education and Athletics, University (Gelman) Library, and Lenthall Houses.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains information concerning the development and fundraising campaigns of the University; endowments; financial gifts; wills; and other gifts. They include correspondence, memorandums, programs, annual fund reports, brochures, newsletters, and endowment reports. They range in date from 1887-2003.
